@NODE 1. "Introduction"

        AlphaSpell  V  is  fast  spelling  checker,  which  finishes  spell
checking a document in a matter of moments. Its speed is due to passing all
the words in the document through each dictionary  in  alphabetical  order,
thereby requiring only a single pass through each dictionary for the entire
document. This is much more efficient than starting at the beginning of the
dictionary for each word. Even more speed  comes  from  reading  compressed
dictionaries and by skipping through the  dictionary  without  reading  and
checking each word. For example, if it is searching for  "love"  and  finds
"label," it will skip past all the remaining  words  beginning  with  "la,"
such as "labels" and "lazy."

        AlphaSpell will also do much more besides spell  checking.  It  has
four different ways to help you correct your misspellings. It  can  measure
rough phonetic similarities between words. It can measure the edit distance
between words, which is the least  number  of  insertions,  deletions,  and
transpositions it takes to change one  word  into  another.  It  can  match
wildcard patterns, and it can list anagrams. These last  two  features  are
also useful for answering crossword puzzles and scrambled word games.

        AlphaSpell also makes it easy to add words to the  dictionary,  and
it lets you customize the dictionaries any way you like.  It  has  features
for removing whole lists of words from dictionaries, as well as for  adding
whole lists of words. You can even add words from  ASCII  dictionaries  you
come across elsewhere.

        AlphaSpell uses two styles of dictionaries for spell  checking.  It
uses lowercase dictionaries for case insensitive spell checking  and  mixed
case dictionaries for case sensitive spell checking. This  is  because  you
want it to recognize some words, such as "This," no matter whether  they're
capitalized or lowercase, but you expect proper names to be capitalized and
acronyms to be entirely in uppercase.  This  feature  keeps  acronyms  from
contaminating the regular dictionary.

        This distribution comes with a GadToolsBox GUI for using AlphaSpell
with the text editor XDME. It is extensively documented, so that others can
use it as a basis for writing a GUI for other editors.

        As of this version, AlphaSpell is shareware rather  than  freeware.
This version is much better than the last version and finally worth  paying
something for. It uses a better compression format for the dictionaries, it
uses proven guessing techniques, and it has  the  new  ability  to  pattern
match. Its dictionaries are cleaner than those in previous versions, and it
is documented much better.

@ENDNODE

