        ftp://sable.ox.ac.uk/pub/wordlists/swedish/words.swedish.Z

        I don't know who originally compiled  the  wordlist.  The  original
wordlist was entirely in 7-bit ASCII, using what I took to be  the  Swedish
character set. So I wrote a conversion script for Rainer Koppler's  program
Cvt, which translates ASCII characters in  the  Swedish  character  set  to
their 8-bit equivalents in ISO Latin.  That  script  is  included  in  this
package.

@ENDNODE

@NODE 12. "Making a dictionary"

        There are at least three ways to make a dictionary. (1) You can
write a wordlist from scratch. (2) You can gather words from files and use
AlphaSpell to list the most frequent words found. (3) You can convert an
already available wordlist into an AlphaSpell dictionary. However you go
about creating a dictionary, there are some things you have to do for any
AlphaSpell dictionary. First, you must make sure that the words in the
dictionary use the ISO Latin character set. This is the character set used
by most Amiga fonts, such as Topaz. Next, you must make sure that any word
whose case doesn't affect its spelling, such as every word in this
sentence, appears in lowercase. Words should be capitalized only if they
must be capitalized in the language you're creating a dictionary for. So
you should capitalize names and German nouns, for example. You should spell
acronyms entirely in capitals. Third, put all the mixed case words in a
file called name.mix, and put all the lowercase words in a file called
name.low. Fourth, sort these files, and make sure you use a case sensitive
sort for the mixed case file. Finally, use AlphaSpell to turn each file
into an AlphaSpell dictionary. AlphaSpell will create an index file for
each dictionary, whose name matches the dictionary name except for the last
two letters, which are "dx."

@ENDNODE
